\\\\n\\\\n\\\\\"C:\\\\\\\\Program Files\\\\\\\\mzmine\\\\\\\\mzmine_consol\",\\n  \"reward\": 1.0\\n}\\n```\\n\\n\\n```json\\n{\\n  \"action\": \"search_tool(query=\\'mzmine macos apple-silicon arm64 installation site:github.com\\')\",\\n  \"observation\": \"Title:ichillous/Brew-Installation-for-MacOS-Apple-Silicon - GitHub\\\\nSnippet:Important: On Apple Silicon Macs, you must use the arch -arm64 prefix before all brew commands to ensure they run natively on the M1 architecture. This includes installation commands, updates, and any other Homebrew operations. For example:\\\\nLink:https://github.com/ichillous/Brew-Installation-for-MacOS-Apple-Silicon\\\\n\\\\nTitle:Releases \\\\u00b7 mzmine/mzmine - GitHub\\\\nSnippet:mzmine 3.9 -> 13.73 GB; mzmine 4.7 -> 1.26 GB (9%) 500 DOM LC-MS files: mzmine 3.9 -> 42.04 GB; mzmine 4.7 -> 3.86 GB (9%) added support for Retention Index extraction ; added support for DIA methods with multiple collision energies (no manual interaction required) fix library generation for GC-EI-MS; added support for MOBILion via MSConvert\\\\nLink:https://github.com/mzmine/mzmine/releases\\\\n\\\\nTitle:How to download mzmine in mac system \\\\u00b7 Issue #2131 - GitHub\\\\nSnippet:I unable to install mzmine at my mac system\\\\nLink:https://github.com/mzmine/mzmine/issues/2131\\\\n\\\\nTitle:Workarounds and Setups for ARM-based Apple-Silicon Mac\\\\nSnippet:Python is natively supported by apple silicon macs. However, at the time of writing, anaconda and miniconda still haven\\'t supported arm yet. The best available is miniforge, a minimal installer for Conda specific to conda-forge. The installation guide can be found on their homepage, but easiest way is to install it with brew.\\\\nLink:https://github.com/mikelxc/Workarounds-for-ARM-mac\\\\n\\\\nTitle:Mzmine 4.2 in macOS \\\\u00b7 mzmine mzmine \\\\u00b7 Discussion #2017 - GitHub\\\\nSnippet:Mzmine 4.2 in macOS. My operating system: macOS Sonoma 14.5 My processor: Dual Core Intel Hello, is the new version of MZmine working on macOS? I have problems installing the app. ... Hello, I\\'m also having problems installing the latest version on Apple silicon mac. Operating system: macOS Sonoma 14.6.1 Processor: Apple M2 Pro.\\\\nLink:https://github.com/mzmine/mzmine/discussions/2017\\\\n\\\\nTitle:GitHub - zhubiaook/arm64-assembly-macos: An introduction to ARM64 ...\\\\nSnippet:In this repository, I will code along with the book Programming with 64-Bit ARM Assembly Language, adjusting all sample code for Apple\\'s ARM64 line of computers. While Apple\\'s marketing material seems to avoid a name for the platform and talks only about the M1 processor, the developer documentation uses the term \\\\\"Apple silicon\\\\\".\\\\nLink:https://github.com/zhubiaook/arm64-assembly-macos\\\\n\\\\nTitle:Install QEMU on Silicon based Apple Macs (June 2021) - GitHub Gist\\\\nSnippet:After upgrading Big Sur & reinstalling the command-line tools, make seems to generate x86_64 object files... this only happened after the update (I think). Any idea what\\'s causing it? Running cc, gcc, or clang without any flags generate arm64, as expected. Even running the very same command that make (ninja) is running generates arm64. But inside the build arch is somehow x64.\\\\nLink:https://gist.github.com/nrjdalal/e70249bb5d2e9d844cc203fd11f74c55\\\\n\\\\nTitle:ComfyUI MacOS Apple Silicon install \\\\u00b7 GitHub\\\\nSnippet:I wonder, does the effort on Apple Silicon makes sense at all unless one converts existing models to apple ML? The standard comfyUI works, I am merely looking for performance enhancement on M1, with things like comfyui-reactor-node on video, etc.\\\\nLink:https://gist.github.com/wouterdebie/b12d5a1160ef9de82cfb7be608f03bdf\\\\n\\\\nTitle:Install node on Apple Silicon M1 both ARM and x86 (Rosetta)\\\\nSnippet:Install node on Apple Silicon M1 both ARM and x86 (Rosetta) - 00_README.md. Install node on Apple Silicon M1 both ARM and x86 (Rosetta) - 00_README.md. Skip to content. ... arm64 is M1. we are not trying to install x86 because that\\'s 32bit and i have a 64 bit OS. the difference between x86 and i386 is irrelevant to me now;\\\\nLink:https://gist.github.com/LeZuse/bf838718ff2689c5fc035c5a6825a11c\\\\n\\\\nTitle:ARM64 Bootloader for Apple Silicon Macs / \\\\u9002\\\\u7528\\\\u4e8e Apple Silicon Mac \\\\u7684 ARM64 ...\\\\nSnippet:# macOS brew install llvm lld python3 dtc # Ubuntu/Debian sudo apt-get install clang lld python3 device-tree-compiler. ... This project is a custom ARM64 bootloader for Apple Silicon Macs, designed to load and boot Android systems\",\\n  \"reward\": 1.0\\n}\\n```\\n\\nLast output from code snippet:\\nNone'}], tool_calls=None, raw=None, token_usage=None)], 'tool_calls': [{'id': 'call_3', 'type': 'function', 'function': {'name': 'python_interpreter', 'arguments': \"final_answer('Here is the detailed summary of my findings:\\\\n\\\\n1. **Batch/Command-Line Options for MZmine**: The official documentation at https://mzmine.github.io/mzmine_documentation/commandline_tool.html and the GitHub repository at https://github.com/mzmine/mzmine_documentation/blob/master/docs/commandline_tool.md provide comprehensive instructions for using MZmine in batch mode. Key flags include `-batch`, `-input`, `-output`, `-login`, and `-memory`. Example usage for processing .mzML files and redirecting outputs is provided.\\\\n\\\\n2. **MacOS Apple-Silicon Installation for MZmine**: No authoritative installation steps for MZmine on MacOS Apple-Silicon (ARM64) systems were found. GitHub issue #2017 (https://github.com/mzmine/mzmine/discussions/2017) mentions installation problems on Apple Silicon Macs but does not provide a solution. There is a gap in the current resources for this specific installation scenario.\\\\n\\\\n**Conclusion**: While MZmine\\\\'s batch processing capabilities are well-documented, the installation process for MacOS Apple-Silicon systems remains unclear and lacks official guidance. Users may need to explore w